Generally there are three ways to connect to a lab machine.

(On the OffSec dashboard, there is a menu on the left hand side.

Under the section "Connectivity" you will see the three options)

Option 1: Click "My Kali" aka  OffSec's Kali In Browser (KIB)

Option 2: Click "My Windows" aka OffSec's Windows' In Browser (WIB) 

For the AI 300 course at the time of writing this note, the recommended method is option 3.

Option 3: Use your own Kali VM and ownload the VPN .ovpn file in the VM.

You will then need to run openvpn to connect to the lab machine.

More detailed steps:

1. Start up your Kali VM and open a browser
2. Log into the OffSec portal and under "connectivity" which appears on the left hand side menu, click "VPN"
3. An openvpn profile will be downloaded onto your machine.
4. Open a terminal in the same folder as your openvpn file (you could move the file to a folder you made for the course)
5. type the ff:
   sudo openvpn --config filename.ovpn

   the terminal will output information , wait until you see "Initialization sequence complete" , seeing that output means that the connection is successful. 

6. After you did this, you can start a lab, so for example , for  lab one, clicking on the lab will create a machine with an IP and credentials - takes about 90 seconds.

7. You sould test connectivity to the lab machine in lab 1 , so you know your vpn is working.

7.1 ping the lab 1 machine ip , it should be successful
7.2 traceroute the lab 1 machine ip, it should be successful
